üß† Introduction


Closures are one of the most powerful‚Äîyet confusing‚Äîfeatures in JavaScript. If you've ever wondered how JavaScript "remembers" variables after a function has run, this post is for you.
By the end, you‚Äôll understand what closures are, why they matter, and how to use them like a pro.
A closure is a function that remembers the variables from its lexical scope, even after that outer function has finished executing.
In simple terms:
A closure lets a function access variables defined outside its scope‚Äîeven after the outer function is done running.
function outer() {
  let count = 0;

  return function inner() {
    count++;
    console.log(`Count is: ${count}`);
  };
}

const counter = outer();

counter(); // Count is: 1
counter(); // Count is: 2
counter(); // Count is: 3

‚úÖ Even though outer() has finished running, inner() still has access to count. That‚Äôs closure in action.
Data Privacy (Encapsulation)





function createSecret() {
  let secret = 'üïµÔ∏è‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è';

  return {
    getSecret: () => secret,
    setSecret: val => secret = val
  };
}

const obj = createSecret();
console.log(obj.getSecret()); // üïµÔ∏è‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è
obj.setSecret('üîê');
console.log(obj.getSecret()); // üîê

üëâ Variables like secret stay hidden from the outside world.
Function Factories





function multiplier(factor) {
  return function (x) {
    return x * factor;
  };
}

const double = multiplier(2);
console.log(double(5)); // 10

üëâ double is a closure that remembers factor = 2.
Closures inside loops can be tricky:
for (var i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
  setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 1000);
}
// Output: 3, 3, 3

let:





for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
  setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 1000);
}
// Output: 0, 1, 2

Closures are everywhere in JavaScript‚Äîfrom callbacks and event handlers to React hooks and private state.
Mastering them will deepen your understanding of how JavaScript really works.
